sentences: Abram Leontievich Markson (Russian: Абрам Леонтьевич Марксон; 1888–1938) was a Russian and Soviet violinist and conductor.
In 1912, he actively gave concerts in Krasnoyarsk as the violinist, having in repertoire masterly products Sarasate Pablo, Venjavsky, K. Sen-Sans, and in 1914 supervised an orchestra of city theatre.

Since 1920, pedagogical activity of Markson in National conservatory, then began musical technical school.
Together with Slovtsov, V. Sokovnin and the chorus master W. V. Abajantsevym, Markson was the founder in 1928 of a philharmonic society «Music to weights".
In February 1938, nine musicians of an orchestra were accused of the White Guard plot and arrested.
On 21 February 1938 Abram Markson, after arrest, was condemned six days NKVD under 58th article and sentenced to a supreme penalty (execution).
The sentence was carried out on 26 February 1938 in Krasnoyarsk.
A.L. Markson was rehabilitated on 15 May 1956 by the military court of the Siberian military district in the absence of crime structure.
